                            text: 'West Coast rock lobster (Jasus lalandii) is found in abundance for commercial exploitation along the west coast of South Africa, as far as Gansbaai. Commercial exploitation of the resource started in the late nineteenth century, yet records of early recreational activity are scant. Historical records do show that the collection of rock lobster has been an important subsistence and/or recreational activity for communities along the west and south-west coasts of South Africa. Before 1983, recreational fishers could fish without a permit, the bag limit was 5 lobsters per day and the minimum size limit was 89mm carapace length (CL). A recreational fishing season was introduced in 1986 from 15 November to 16 April. The total allowable catch (TAC) for the entire sector dropped from what was >6000 tons in the 1970s to ~2500 tons from the mid-1990s, due to a significant drop in somatic growth rate that occurred at the end of the 1980s. The TAC has continued to decline and has remained below 2000 tons since 2014. The allocation to the recreational sector is a total applied effort (TAE) of fishing days with identified dates within the season that fishers may harvest on. In recent years, the number of fishing days allocated to the recreational sector was 21 fishing days and has declined to a meagre 12 fishing days.'
